1.2 Distribution and correlation of predictors

do_env = ggpairs(data, columns = c(21:25), lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", alpha = 0.3, size = 0.7)))+
  theme_classic()
do_env

All environmental variables are more or less normally distributed and slightly correlated to each other. It should be checked whether multicollinearity is present or not.

1.3 Collinearity

Checking for collinearity with variance inflation parameter (VIF) 

vif(lm(spp1 ~ env1 + env2 + env3 + env4 + env5, data = data))
##     env1     env2     env3     env4     env5 
## 1.051096 1.207088 1.130897 1.122332 1.124196

All VIF for predictors are far below 5, hence there is no problematic collinearity

2 Linear models using stepwise model selection

2.1 Intercept and full model

To apply stepwise model selection, the intercept model (model without any environmental predictor) and the full model (model with all environmental parameters as predictors) must be specified 

intercept_model = lm(spp16 ~ 1, data = data)


full_model = lm(spp16 ~ env1 + env2 + env3 + env4 + env5, data = data)

2.2 Not including interaction terms

2.2.1 Forward stepwise model selection (no interaction)

for_lm = step(intercept_model, scope=formula(full_model), directions = "forward")

2.2.4 Model diagnosis

plot(for_lm)

Assumptions are fulfilled:

  • residuals are homogeneous (Homoscedasticity)
  • Normal distribution of error
  • There are no infuential outliers
  • Observations should be independent, but data source is unknown
  • Linearity has been checked in line 96
  • Multicollinearity has been excluded in line 54 
summary(for_lm)
##

2.3.4 Diagnosis and interpretation

2.3.4.1 Forward and both directions stepwise model selection

Both resulted in the same model

plot(for_lm_int)

Assumptions for forward and both direction stepwise selection models are fulfilled:

  • residuals are homogeneous (Homoscedasticity)
  • Normal distribution of error
  • There are no infuential outliers
  • Observations should be independent, but data source is unknown
  • Linearity has been checked in line 96
  • Multicollinearity has been excluded in line 54

2.3.4.2 Backward model selection

plot(back_lm_int)

Assumptions for backward stepwise selection model are not completely fulfilled:

  • residuals are only more or less homogeneous (Homoscedasticity)
  • Error is normally distributed although not as clearly as the previous models
  • There are at least two infuential outliers
  • Observations should be independent, but data source is unknown
  • Linearity has been checked in data exploration
  • Multicollinearity is present due to interaction terms (see below)

Checking for multilinearity in the linear model with interaction terms: 

vif(lm(spp1 ~ env1 * env2 * env3 * env4, data = data))

4 Redundancy analysis (RDA)

4.1 Hellinger transformation

First to run the RDA, the abundance data must be transformed to fulfill the assumptions for multiple linear regression (normal distribution and constant variance) For that the Hellinger transformation is used 

sp.hellinger = decostand(sp, method = "hellinger")

sp.melt = melt(sp)
## Using  as id variables
sp.h.melt = melt(sp.hellinger)
## Using  as id variables
ggplot(sp.melt, aes(x=value, fill=variable)) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.6) + xlim(0,70) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete=TRUE) +
  scale_color_viridis(discrete=TRUE) +
  ylab("Density") +
  xlab("Abundance value")

Distribution of untransformed abundances 

ggplot(sp.h.melt, aes(x=value, fill=variable)) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.6) + xlim(0,0.4) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete=TRUE) +
  scale_color_viridis(discrete=TRUE) +
  ylab("Density") +
  xlab("Abundance value (Hellinger transformed")

Distribution of Hellinger transformed abundances

Hellinger transformation lead to more normally distributed abundances
